# Session Wrap-Up

When implementation work appears finished, **proactively suggest wrap-up** before moving on. Do not commit or open a PR unless the user explicitly agrees to wrap-up.

## When to suggest wrap-up

Offer wrap-up when any of these apply:

- A feature, bugfix, or refactor looks complete
- The user signals done ("thanks", "looks good", "that's it", "ship it", etc.)
- You are about to end your turn after substantive code changes
- **Session start**: run `git status` (and `git diff --stat` if dirty); if there are uncommitted changes, briefly note them and ask whether to finalize now

Do **not** suggest wrap-up after pure Q&A, exploration-only turns, or when the user clearly wants to continue iterating.

## How to suggest

Use a short, direct offer — one paragraph, not a lecture. Example:

> This looks complete. Want me to run wrap-up? I'll review the diff, run tests, get us on a ticket branch, commit, and open a PR to main.

If the user agrees (or says "wrap up", "finalize", etc.), read and follow `.cursor/skills/session-finalize/SKILL.md` end-to-end.

## Constraints

- **Never commit or open a PR** without explicit user approval (agreeing to wrap-up counts)
- **Run tests** during wrap-up (`python -m pytest tests/` when a test suite exists) before committing
- Keep suggestions brief; do not nag repeatedly in the same session after the user declines
